Gilleen data behavioural analyses of PDG and beads tasks

Gary Napier

12 August 2016

Three datasets:

  • PDG action for each round (compete /cooperate);
  • PDG trust rating (0 = totally untrustworthy, 1 = totally trustworthy, 0.5 = unsure) and
  • Beads (0 = definitely jar A, 1 = definitely jar B, 0.5 = unsure).

Four sequences:

  • PDG task: Seq A = mostly cooperative, Seq D = mostly competitive, Seq B = first half mostly cooperative switching to second half mostly competitive, and Seq C vice versa.
  • Beads task: As the PDG task except ‘comptetitive’ and ‘cooperative’ replaced by ‘Jar A’ and ‘Jar B’

Questions - Are there group differences in:

  1. First half ‘draws to certainty (DTC)’ - How many trials until subjects reach maximum certainty (1 or 0) in the first half of either task. Also, how many subjects, as a proportion of group numbers, reach maximum certainty at which trial indeces?

  2. Second half DTC - How many trials until subjects reach maximum certainty after the change of jar/trustworthiness in Seq B and Seq C only.

  3. The initial decision whether to cooperate/compete in the PDG in all four sequences.

  4. The average trust ratings on each trial the same in Seq A and Seq D (‘mostly cooperate’, ‘mostly compete’, respectively).
